==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Etymology
<hw>Et`y*mol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(-j⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Etymologies</plw> <pr>(-j⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L.<ets>etymologia</ets>, Gr. <grk>'etymologi`a</grk>;
<grk>'e`tymon</grk> etymon + <grk>lo`gos</grk> discourse, description:
cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tymologie</ets>. See <er>Etymon</er>, and
<er>-logy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That branch of philological
science which treats of the history of words, tracing out their origin,
primitive significance, and changes of form and meaning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That part of grammar which relates to the changes in
the form of the words in a language; inflection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Etymon</ent>⟦br⟧
